{"title_page": "Juli\u00e1n Bonequi", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Juli\u00e1n Bonequi\n| image                 = Julianbonequi.jpg\n| caption            = Juli\u00e1n 2007 at Pompeu Fabra University Studio\n| image_size            = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = Julian Bonequi\n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|1974|12|27}}\n| death_date                = \n| origin              = Mexico City, Mexico\n| instrument          = [[Drums]], [[Vocals]], [[Electronics]]\n| occupation          = musician, [[3d artist|sonor artist]]\n| years_active        = 1995\u2013present\n| label               = [[Audition Records]], [[Discordian Records]], [[Re:konstruKt Istanbul]], [[Radical Matters]], [[Jazzorca Records]], [[Musea]], [[Surrism-Phonoethics]], [[AMP Records]], [[Mandorla]], [[Headphonica]], [[Audioatalaia]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Ultraspie\u00dfer]], [[Berlin Improvisers Orchestra]], [[Machinations of Joy]], [[Orquesta FOCO]], [[Los Idiotes]], [[Decibel (band)|Decibel]], [[Pandillismo]].\n| website                 = [http://www.julianbonequi.com]\n}}\n\n'''Juli\u00e1n Bonequi''' (born December 27, 1974) is a [[Mexican people|Mexican]] artist working mostly with [[Noise]] and [[Improvisation]] and [[3d computer graphics]]<ref name=\"Lecture Notes in Computer Science\">Springerlink [https://doi.org/10.1007%2F978-3-642-14061-7_26]''Articulated Motion and Deformable Objects'',Springer Berlin / Heidelberg</ref> He plays the drums, and experiments with electronics and voice to create a rhythmic environment much richer in atmospheres and harmonic flow situations. He played in the [[FOCO Orchestra]] (Orquesta FOCO - Madrid) (2006\u20132011), and create with [[Dave Tucker (drummer)|Dave Tucker]]<ref name=\"DaveTucker\">Pax Recordings. [http://www.paxrecordings.com/Artists/Dave_Tucker.html Dave Tucker] ''Take a word of a madman'', Composer.</ref><ref name=\"Dave Tucker\">All About Jazz. [https://archive.today/20130101184701/http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/musician.php?id=14351 Music Improvisation] ''Dave Tucker'', Biography.</ref> and [[Ricardo Tejero]] the project [[Machinations of Joy]]\n\nJulian Bonequi established himself in Barcelona within the Spanish improvisation free jazz music scene since 2004, but has since also performed with a wide range of musicians working in diverse musical areas since he lived in Mexico. He has performed as guest with the London Improvisers Orchestra as electronic voice, attracted by the roots of free improvisation\n\nFrom 1995 to 2000 he participated in several projects of [[folklore]], [[Rock in Opposition]] and [[psychedelia]] in Mexico City.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n===Early life===\nSince 1995 he played in a lot of [[Punk rock|punk]], [[psycodelia]], [[stone rock]] and [[progressive rock]] projects, but always trying to give 100% importance to the freedom that improvisation gives to music.\n\nHe played with [[Humus (band)]] that was founded in 1987 by [[Jorge Beltr\u00e1n]] (guitar, keyboards) and [[Victor Basurto]] the full-fledged bassist. Both of them, are formers musician of many other important Mexican bands, as [[Frolic Froth]], [[Smoking The Century Away]], [[Euphoric Darkness]], [[Loch Ness]] and [[Semefo]]. Since 1997 Westminster became more or less the permanent drummer of [[Humus]], who was preceded by Julian Bonequi (1998\u20132000) when Jorge Beltr\u00e1n invited Bonequi to make important contributions to different albums (not yet released).<ref name=\"Humus1998\">Obvious Duality. [http://www.soundclick.com/bands/page_music.cfm?bandID=801344 Humus] ''Unrealesed Material'', Mexico, 1998.</ref><ref name=\"Humus\">Old Recordings.[http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view&friendId=198355448&blogId=346127982 Humus Not Yet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207065936/http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view |date=2009-02-07 }} ''Unrealesed'', Mexico, 1998.</ref>\n\nIn 1999 he met [[Decibel (band)|Decibel]].<ref name=\"Decibel2000\">Fiat Lux. The Complete Recordings 1977-2000. [http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/1513 Decibel] ''MIO Records'', Israel, 2000.</ref> Decibel were a rare exception to the prog acts of the 1978 period in Mexico, and were well versed in European groups such as [[Faust (band)|Faust]], [[Magma (band)|Magma]], [[Gong (band)|Gong]], and the Italian prog masters [[Il Balletto di Bronzo]]. The lineup centered around keyboardist [[Carlos Robledo]] and the bassist [[Walter Schmidt (musician)|Walter Schmidt]]. So he found finally a place for improve his skills and experiment more. With them Julian Bonequi perform in the First [[International Festival of Progressive Rock]] in Mexico City, with Magma and Gong also in the program.\nAnd the next year, in March 2000 in a concert in the [[Museum Ex-Teresa Arte Actual]] in the historic centre of Mexico City, they celebrated the 25th anniversary and present the CD release named [[Fortuna Virilis]], in addition to a retrospective with the work done since 1974. This concert is included in the three-disc box [[Fiat Lux]], and it was the last time Decibel, this legendary Mexican band of Rock In Opposition play together without [[Javier Baviera]], or [[Jaime Castaneda]], but with Julian Bonequi on drums and [[Juan Carlos Ruiz]] on bassoon, former musician of [[Nazca]], and leader of [[Culto Sin Nombre]]\n\nThe same year, in 2000, the Israeli Label, [[MIO Records]] produced a 3-disc box called ''[[Fiat Lux. The complete recordings]]''. 1977 - 2000, which contains all the studio albums of Decibel, and plus live material and rarities of unedited material. And a small booklet of 28 pages with pictures of the beginnings of the band. Also this box contained the 25th anniversary concert at Ex-Teresa Arte Actual.\n\nWith [[Metaconciencia]] Julian Bonequi recorded the first album \"[[Bestiario]]\" in 2003 published by the French record label [[MUSEA]] Records. The critics received well this music work. A rhythm section perform a colourful and warm instrumental rock with multiple influences: [[Seventies Progressive rock]], [[jazz-rock]], [[Mexican music]] The music presented in Bestiario is quite intensive all of which is accompanied by quite an extraordinary drumming.\n<ref name=\"Metaconciencia\">Bestiario. [http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/6754384/a/Bestiario.htm Metaconciencia] ''Musea Records'', France, 2003.</ref><ref name=\"Metaconciencia2003\">Bestiario. [http://www.progressor.net/review/metaconciencia_2003.html Detailed Reviews] ''Progressor'', Uzbekistan, 2003.</ref>\n\n===Spain/London===\n[[Image:Machinations of Joy.jpg|thumb|150px|left|[[Machinations of Joy (album)|Machinations of Joy]] with Dave Tucker]]Since 2007, based in Barcelona, he played as drummer and percussionist with the [[FOCO Orchestra]] of Madrid. An active member of the [[Collective of Spanish improvisers]] [[Musicalibre]] and the [[FOCO Orchestra]]. Guest of London Improvisers Orchestra (2008\u20132009) in the 10th Anniversary of LIO and in Freedom of the City Festival at Conway Hall (voice/electronics).\n\nIn the edition of the Festival [[Hurta Cordel]], celebrated the last week of January 2009, FOCO was conducted by New York experimental jazz composer& musician, William Parker, and they present together in the Palau de la Musica Catalana in Barcelona.<ref name=\"WilliamParker\">FOCO Orchestra [http://www.elperiodico.com/default.asp?idpublicacio_PK=46&idioma=CAS&idnoticia_PK=584811&idseccio_PK=1013 William Parker] ''El Peri\u00f3dico'', Palau de la Musica, 2009.</ref> In 2010 the conductor was the improviser legend, Keith Tippett.\n\n===Berlin===\n\n[[Edu Comelles]]<ref name=\"Edu Comelles\">[[Edu Comelles]][http://www.educomelles.com/] Sound Artist</ref> ( Coordinator and Creator of [[Audiotalaia]] )<ref name=\"Audiotalaia\">[[Audiotalaia]] [http://www.audiotalaia.net/home.html Audioatalaia Netlabel]</ref>  a Catalan Sound Artist living in [[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]], and Julian Bonequi ( Project manager and curator ) living since 2010 in Berlin. They decided to create '''[[Audition Records]]'''.<ref name=\"Audition Records\">[[Audition Records]][http://www.auditions.com/home.html] About Audition Records</ref> Audition Records documents the development of Improvisation in Europe by both native musicians and international ones who have settled here\u2014 musicians whose curiosity extends their sonority concepts all over the world.\n\nJulian Bonequi, resident artist at [[NK Projekt]] in 2010,<ref name=\"NK, Sound Arts, Berlin\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nkprojekt.de/ |title=NK |access-date=2020-02-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629190525/http://www.nkprojekt.de/ |archive-date=2019-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> an artist run independent non-profit organization that is dedicated to Sound Arts in Berlin, taking part in the creation and support of a \"culture\" with a focus on experimental music. Bonequi announced NK as new collaborator of Audition Records, and they decided together to publish selected concerts and performances in agreement with the artists.<ref name=\"Mat Pogo live at NK\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar003.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707185016/http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar003.html|url-status=dead|title=Mat Pogo|archivedate=July 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Joke Lanz live at NK\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar004.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707185157/http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar004.html|url-status=dead|title=Joke Lanz|archivedate=July 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nCurating and coordinating series in Berlin as associate curator, promoter or project manager since 2012. He was involved in the [[Ohrengala]]<ref name=\"Ohrengala\">[[Ohrengala]][http://www.auditionrecords.com/ohrengala.php] Regular experimental serie organised at Bei Roy</ref> at Bei Roy, collaborating until October 2012, in [[RAM]],<ref name=\"RAM\">[[RAM]][http://www.auditionrecords.com/ram.php] Radical Animation and Musik 2012, Audition Records-Salon Bruit</ref> Radical Animation and Musik at K77 in collaboration with [[Salon Bruit]],<ref name=\"Salon Bruit\">[[Salon Bruit]][http://salonbruit.org/artists/julian-bonequi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128102200/http://salonbruit.org/artists/julian-bonequi |date=2015-11-28 }} Julian Bonequi,  Salon Bruit</ref> and in the female soloist serie and documentary episodes in Berlin around improvised, noise and electroacoustic music and contemporary composers, started in February 2013 named [[Quota;unquota]]<ref name=\"Quota\">[[Quot;unquota]][http://www.auditionrecords.com/quota.php] Female Soloists In Berlin, Quota;Unquota</ref> co-curated by [[Philip Morris (musician)|Philip Morris]] aka Sciolist. In winter 2012 Bonequi moved again from Berlin to Mexico City, where he runs and coordinates Audition Records Berlin expanding Audition Records activities to Mexico City.<ref name=\"Audition Records Mexico\">[[Audition Records Mexico]][http://www.auditionrecords.com/mx.php] Audition Records in Mexico</ref>\n\n===Istanbul===\n\nJanuary 2011, [[Audition Records]] announced a new collaboration with re:kontruKt Istanbul Label after a recording with Korhan Futac\u0131 (voice, sax, zurna), Umut \u00c7a\u011flar (guitar), Barlas Tan \u00d6zemek (guitar) & Yasemin Mori (voice on track 4 & 5), catalogued re044: The Sun, the Moon & the Stars.<ref name=\"044: re:konstrukt\">[http://rekonstrukt.com/] re044:  The Sun, the Moon & the Stars</ref> [[Umut Caglar]] is the curator and project manager of [[re:konstrukt]]<ref name=\"re:konstrukt\">[[re:konstrukt]]{{cite web |url=http://auditionrecords.com/ar016.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707185111/http://auditionrecords.com/ar016.html |archivedate=2011-07-07 }} ar016: RE:KONSTRUKT - Istanbul. IMPROVISED MUSIC LABEL</ref> label.\n\n===Vienna===\n\nMarch 2011: New documents collected in Vienna are published in [[Audition Records]] as part from one of the strongest scenes happening in Vienna and working hard since eleven years ago in Austria. Conversations with [[Dieb13]]<ref name=\"Dieb13\">[[Dieb13]]{{cite web |url=http://auditionrecords.com/ar018.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504012635/http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar018.html |archivedate=2011-05-04 }} ar018: Dieb13 - Conversations</ref> about [[klingt.org]]<ref name=\"klingt.org\">[[klingt.org]]{{cite web |url=http://auditionrecords.com/ar019.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502140412/http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar019.html |archivedate=2011-05-02 }} ar019: klingt.org - 11th Years of Experimental Music</ref>\n\n===Krems===\n\nFrom 14 to 24 February 2011 Julian led a workshop for the 8B from the Borg Krems. There he showed the students how to work in Mudbox and what they could do in Maya. As a present he received a bottle of wine. In February 2011 Bonequi worked and lived in Krems as Resident Artist at [[Air-Krems]]:<ref name=\"Air-Krems\">[[Air-Krems]][http://www.air-krems.at/archive/2011/julian-bonequi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045402/http://www.air-krems.at/archive/2011/julian-bonequi |date=2016-03-04 }} Julian Bonequi, Artist in Residence</ref> \"... Each day we recorded 15 to 30 minutes of short improvisations, then we edited it and mixed, without overdubs. Always respecting the original improvisation and following differents rules we determined before we played...\"\n\n===Mexico City===\n\nSpring 2013. [[Audition Records]] announces  \"The Mexican Tour, 8 dates, 5 cities: Mexico City, Guanajuato, Quer\u00e9taro, Tlaxcala, Guadalajara\"<ref name=\"MoE, The Mexican Tour\">[[MoE]] [http://www.auditionrecords.com/moe.php] Splits gigs MoE/Bonequi</ref> - Splits gigs with the Norwegian rock noise trio [[MoE]],<ref name=\"MoE\">[[MoE]][http://www.conradsound.com/] Rock Noise From Norway, MoE</ref> organized by [[Audition Records]], and Bonequi coordinating the Tour Management, Logistics and Documentation and performing as soloist as previous act.<ref name=\"Bonequi, The Mexican Tour\">Julian Bonequi [http://www.auditionrecords.com/bonequi.php] Splits gigs MoE/Bonequi</ref>\n\n== Releases ==\n\n=== Improvised Music ===\n* ''[[Tabla y Cuchillo]]''<ref name=\"Tabla y Cuchillo\">Tabla y Cuchillo: Ricardo Tejero, Niko Meinhold & Bonequi  [http://auditionrecords.com/rtma/archives/arm009.html] ''RTMA'', Berlin, 2012</ref> Recorded at Liegnitzer Stra\u00dfe 16, Berlin (2012)\n* ''[[Ultraspie\u00dfer]] (Extended Version)''<ref name=\"Ultraspie\u00dfer\">Ultraspie\u00dfer:  Anton Maiof, Ratbag (Julian Percy) & Bonequi  [http://www.radicalmatters.com/radical.matters.cd.cdr.catalogue.asp?tp=1&c=381] ''RadicalMatters EditionsLabel'', Italy, 2012</ref> Recorded at NK Projekt, Berlin (2011)\n* ''[[Matarratas]] (Extended Version)''<ref name=\"Matarratas\">Matarratas:  Ratbag (Julian Percy) & Bonequi  [http://www.radicalmatters.com/radical.matters.cd.cdr.catalogue.asp?tp=1&c=380] ''RadicalMatters EditionsLabel'', Italy, 2012</ref> Recorded at NK Projekt, Berlin (2011)\n* ''[[Reflexiones Ac\u00fasticas]]''<ref name=\"Acpustic Reflections\">Julian Bonequi [http://auditionrecords.com/rtma/archives/arm007.html] ''realtime music archives'', Berlin, Krems, 2011</ref> Recorded at [[NK Projekt|NK]], [[Air-Krems]], (2011)\n* ''[[Sangre Azteca]]''<ref name=\"Sangre Azteca\">Julian Bonequi [http://rekonstrukt.com/re_konstrukt/054.html] ''re:konstruKt'', Istanbul, 2011</ref> Recorded at [[NK Projekt|NK]]- Berlin (2011)\n* ''[[Reptilian Mambo]]''<ref name=\"Reptilian Mambo\">Don Malfon, El Pricto, Martin Del Litto, Avelino Saavedra & Julian Bonequi [http://discordianrecords.bandcamp.com/album/reptilian-mambo] ''discordian records'', Barcelona, 2011</ref> Recorded at [[The Hodge Podge St.]] (2011)\n* ''[[Angry Lords]]''<ref name=\"Angry Lords\">Julian Bonequi [http://auditionrecords.com/rtma/archives/arm005.html] ''realtime music archives'', Berlin, Krems, Barcelona, 2011</ref> Recorded at [[NK Projekt|NK]], [[Air-Krems]], [[Discordian Records]] (2011)\n* ''[[Comechingones]]''<ref name=\"Comechingones\">Julian Bonequi & El Pricto [http://discordianrecords.bandcamp.com/album/comechingones] ''discordian records'', Barcelona, 2011</ref> Recorded at [[The Hodge Podge St.]] (2011)\n* ''[[The Third Mind]]''<ref name=\"The Third Mind\">Don Malfon, Alvaro Rosso, Julian Bonequi & El Pricto [http://discordianrecords.bandcamp.com/album/the-third-mind] ''discordian records'', Barcelona, 2011</ref> Recorded at [[The Hodge Podge St.]] (2011)\n* ''[[Ultraspei\u00dfer]]''<ref name=\"Ultraspei\u00dfer\">Ratbag, Anton Anton Maiof & Julian Bonequi [http://auditionrecords.com/rtma/archives/arm006.html] ''realtime music archives'', Berlin, 2010</ref> Recorded at [[NK Projekt|NK]], (2011)\n* ''[[ar027 Pandillismo]]''<ref name=\"Pandillismo 2011\">Rogelio Sosa, Mario de Vega, Juan Pablo Villa & Julian Bonequi {{cite web |url=http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar027.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902135325/http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar027.html |archivedate=2011-09-02 }} ''audition records'', Barcelona, 2011</ref> Recorded at [[Hurta Cordel]] (2010)\n* ''[[044 The Sun, The Moon & The Stars]]''<ref name=\"The Sun, The Moon & The Stars 2011\">Korhan Futac\u0131, Umut \u00c7a\u011flar, Barlas Tan \u00d6zemek, Yasemin Mori & Julian Bonequi [http://rekonstrukt.com] ''re:konstruKt'', Istanbul, 2011</ref> Recorded at [[re:konstruKt Istanbul]] (2011)\n* ''[[arm001 Matarratas]]''<ref name=\"Matarratas 2011\">Ratbag & Julian Bonequi [http://auditionrecords.com/rtma/archives/arm001.html] [[Realtime Music Archives]]'', Berlin, 2010</ref> Recorded at [[NK Projekt]] (2010)\n* ''[[Tabla y Cuchillo]]''<ref name=\"Tabla y Cuchillo 2011\">Julian Bonequi & Ricardo Tejero [http://surrism.phonoethics.com/surrism-phonoethics_tabla_y_cuchillo_spe_0091.html] [[Surrism-Phonoethics]]'', Frankfurt, 2010</ref> Recorded at [[Rupprechtstra\u00dfe 20]] (2011)\n* ''[[Berlin Improvisers Orchestra]]''<ref name=\"BERIO 2010\">Berlin Improvisers Orchestra [https://web.archive.org/web/20110125225115/http://auditionrecords.com/ar009.html] ''Audition Records'', Berlin, 2010</ref> Recorded at [[wendel - Nstp.de]],<ref name=\"wendel - Nstp.de\">wendel - Nstp.de [http://www.nstp.de/nstp/frameset-wendel.htm] ''wendel - Nstp.de'', Venues in Berlin</ref> Berlin (2010)\n* ''[[NK Rekordings]]''<ref name=\"NK Rekordings2010\">Julian Bonequi Improvisations -jb001- [http://amp-recs.com/amp/amp071.html] ''AMP Records Label'', Mexico, 2010</ref> Recorded at [[NK Projekt]], Berlin (2010)\n*''[[Machinations of Joy]]''.<ref name=\"MachinationsofJoy2010\">Music Technology Group St.Sessions. [http://www.audiotalaia.net/at027.html Machinations of Joy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128115302/http://www.audiotalaia.net/at027.html |date=2010-01-28 }} ''Audioatalaia Net Label'', Barcelona, January 15, 2010.</ref> \"Audiotalaia Netlabel\" [[Music Technology Group]] St. [[Universitat Pompeu Fabra]]. Barcelona (2010)\n*''[[Los Idiotes]]''<ref name=\"LosIdiotes2009\">Universitat Pompeu Fabra St.Sessions. [http://www.amp-recs.com/amp/amp043.html Los Idiotes] ''AMP Records Label'', Mexico, 2009.</ref>  \"A.M.P. Records\" [[Music Technology Group]] St. [[Universitat Pompeu Fabra]]. Barcelona-Mexico(2009)\n*''[[Decibel]] Fiat Lux, The complete recordings. 1977 to 2000''. \"MIO Records\". Israel (2000)\n*''[[Hans Tammen - Ursel Schlicht]] Statements en Mexico''. [[CONACULTA]] and [[Fundaci\u00f3n BBVA Bancomer]] (2000)\n\n=== NetCompilations ===\n* ''[[Discordian Records]]'', 2011-2012 Barcelona<ref name=\"Discordian Records\">Discordian Records - Promotional Compilation  [http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar079.php] ''Audition Records'', Berlin, 2012</ref> Recorded at [[The Hodge Podge St.]] (2012)\n*'' [[New Weird Berlin Compilation]]''<ref name=\"ew Weird Berlin Compilation2010\">Ratbag+Bonequi  {{cite web |url=http://www.weirdandwired.net/label/waw036-new-weird-berlin/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724130431/http://www.weirdandwired.net/label/waw036-new-weird-berlin/ |archivedate=2011-07-24 }} ''WeirdAndWired'', Berlin, 2010.</ref> Recorded at [[NK Projekt]] (2010)\n*''Julian Bonequi & [[Eduardo Melendez]]''. \"Sous les pieds Remix Project\". [[Headphonica]] NetLabel. France(2009)\n*''Julian Bonequi & [[Kenji Siratori]]'' \"Mandorla Autum Net Project\" (2009)\n\n=== NetCollaborations ===\n*''[[Sara Herculano]] SHHHHH!'' \"A.M.P. Record Label\" Spain-Mexico (2009)\n*''[[The Beauty Noise]]''<ref name=\"TheBeautyNOise2009\">The Beauty Noise Vol.I. [http://www.amp-recs.com/amp/amp036.html Featuring Kenji Siratori] ''AMP Records Label'', Barcelona, 2009.</ref> Featuring [[Kenji Siratori]] \"AMP Records\" (2009)\n\n=== Guest/Releases ===\n*''[[H\u00edbridos]] Jos\u00e9 Luis Fern\u00e1ndez Ledesma'' \"Luna Records\" Mexico(2007)\n*''[[La Paciencia de Job]]'' \"Musea Records\". Les Classiques du Futur. France(2004)\n*''[[Metaconciencia]]'' Bestiario, \"Musea Records\" France (2003)\n*''[[Smoking the Century Away]]'' \"Nuggetphase Records\". The Netherlands(2001)\n\n== Netaudio ==\n*''Not Me'',<ref name=\"Impronet\">Julian Bonequi Improvisation - Impro 44 [http://audioblog.arteradio.com//impronet/frontUser.do?method=getHomePage] ''Impronet'', Berlin 2010</ref> Impronet: The Improvisators Network\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.julianbonequi.com/ web Julian Bonequi]\n*[http://www.auditionrecords.com/ web Audition Records]\n*[http://www.auditionrecords.com/quota.php web Female Soloists in Berlin]\n*[http://www.auditionrecords.com/ram.php web Radical Animation & Musik]\n*[http://www.auditionrecords.com/bonequi.php web Alienated Rituals]\n*[http://www.asociacionmusicalibre.com Musicalibre Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130115121318/http://www.audiotalaia.net/catalogue/at027/ audiotalaia netlabel: Machinations of Joy]\n*[http://www.amp-recs.com/downloads.html AMP Records Label]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonequi, Julian}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican musicians]]\n[[Category:Musea artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Juli\u00e1n Bonequi\n| image                 = Julianbonequi.jpg\n| caption            = Juli\u00e1n 2007 at Pompeu Fabra University Studio\n| image_size            = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = Julian Bonequi\n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|1974|12|27}}\n| death_date                = \n| origin              = Mexico City, Mexico\n| instrument          = [[Drums]], [[Vocals]], [[Electronics]]\n| occupation          = musician, [[3d artist|sonor artist]]\n| years_active        = 1995\u2013present\n| label               = [[Audition Records]], [[Discordian Records]], [[Re:konstruKt Istanbul]], [[Radical Matters]], [[Jazzorca Records]], [[Musea]], [[Surrism-Phonoethics]], [[AMP Records]], [[Mandorla]], [[Headphonica]], [[Audioatalaia]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Ultraspie\u00dfer]], [[Berlin Improvisers Orchestra]], [[Machinations of Joy]], [[Orquesta FOCO]], [[Los Idiotes]], [[Decibel (band)|Decibel]], [[Pandillismo]].\n| website                 = [http://www.julianbonequi.com]\n}}\n\n'''Juli\u00e1n Bonequi''' (born December 27, 1974) is a [[Mexican people|Mexican]] artist working mostly with [[Noise]] and [[Improvisation]] and [[3d computer graphics]]<ref name=\"Lecture Notes in Computer Science\">Springerlink [https://doi.org/10.1007%2F978-3-642-14061-7_26]''Articulated Motion and Deformable Objects'',Springer Berlin / Heidelberg</ref> He plays the drums, and experiments with electronics and voice to create a rhythmic environment much richer in atmospheres and harmonic flow situations. He played in the [[FOCO Orchestra]] (Orquesta FOCO - Madrid) (2006\u20132011), and create with [[Dave Tucker (drummer)|Dave Tucker]]<ref name=\"DaveTucker\">Pax Recordings. [http://www.paxrecordings.com/Artists/Dave_Tucker.html Dave Tucker] ''Take a word of a madman'', Composer.</ref><ref name=\"Dave Tucker\">All About Jazz. [https://archive.today/20130101184701/http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/musician.php?id=14351 Music Improvisation] ''Dave Tucker'', Biography.</ref> and [[Ricardo Tejero]] the project [[Machinations of Joy]]\n\nJulian Bonequi established himself in Barcelona within the Spanish improvisation free jazz music scene since 2004, but has since also performed with a wide range of musicians working in diverse musical areas since he lived in Mexico. He has performed as guest with the London Improvisers Orchestra as electronic voice, attracted by the roots of free improvisation\n\nFrom 1995 to 2000 he participated in several projects of [[folklore]], [[Rock in Opposition]] and [[psychedelia]] in Mexico City.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n===Early life===\nSince 1995 he played in a lot of [[Punk rock|punk]], [[psycodelia]], [[stone rock]] and [[progressive rock]] projects, but always trying to give 100% importance to the freedom that improvisation gives to music.\n\nHe played with [[Humus (band)]] that was founded in 1987 by [[Jorge Beltr\u00e1n]] (guitar, keyboards) and [[Victor Basurto]] the full-fledged bassist. Both of them, are formers musician of many other important Mexican bands, as [[Frolic Froth]], [[Smoking The Century Away]], [[Euphoric Darkness]], [[Loch Ness]] and [[Semefo]]. Since 1997 Westminster became more or less the permanent drummer of [[Humus]], who was preceded by Julian Bonequi (1998\u20132000) when Jorge Beltr\u00e1n invited Bonequi to make important contributions to different albums (not yet released).<ref name=\"Humus1998\">Obvious Duality. [http://www.soundclick.com/bands/page_music.cfm?bandID=801344 Humus] ''Unrealesed Material'', Mexico, 1998.</ref><ref name=\"Humus\">Old Recordings.[http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view&friendId=198355448&blogId=346127982 Humus Not Yet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207065936/http://blogs.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=blog.view |date=2009-02-07 }} ''Unrealesed'', Mexico, 1998.</ref>\n\nIn 1999 he met [[Decibel (band)|Decibel]].<ref name=\"Decibel2000\">Fiat Lux. The Complete Recordings 1977-2000. [http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/1513 Decibel] ''MIO Records'', Israel, 2000.</ref> Decibel were a rare exception to the prog acts of the 1978 period in Mexico, and were well versed in European groups such as [[Faust (band)|Faust]], [[Magma (band)|Magma]], [[Gong (band)|Gong]], and the Italian prog masters [[Il Balletto di Bronzo]]. The lineup centered around keyboardist [[Carlos Robledo]] and the bassist [[Walter Schmidt (musician)|Walter Schmidt]]. So he found finally a place for improve his skills and experiment more. With them Julian Bonequi perform in the First [[International Festival of Progressive Rock]] in Mexico City, with Magma and Gong also in the program.\nAnd the next year, in March 2000 in a concert in the [[Museum Ex-Teresa Arte Actual]] in the historic centre of Mexico City, they celebrated the 25th anniversary and present the CD release named [[Fortuna Virilis]], in addition to a retrospective with the work done since 1974. This concert is included in the three-disc box [[Fiat Lux]], and it was the last time Decibel, this legendary Mexican band of Rock In Opposition play together without [[Javier Baviera]], or [[Jaime Castaneda]], but with Julian Bonequi on drums and [[Juan Carlos Ruiz]] on bassoon, former musician of [[Nazca]], and leader of [[Culto Sin Nombre]]\n\nThe same year, in 2000, the Israeli Label, [[MIO Records]] produced a 3-disc box called ''[[Fiat Lux. The complete recordings]]''. 1977 - 2000, which contains all the studio albums of Decibel, and plus live material and rarities of unedited material. And a small booklet of 28 pages with pictures of the beginnings of the band. Also this box contained the 25th anniversary concert at Ex-Teresa Arte Actual.\n\nWith [[Metaconciencia]] Julian Bonequi recorded the first album \"[[Bestiario]]\" in 2003 published by the French record label [[MUSEA]] Records. The critics received well this music work. A rhythm section perform a colourful and warm instrumental rock with multiple influences: [[Seventies Progressive rock]], [[jazz-rock]], [[Mexican music]] The music presented in Bestiario is quite intensive all of which is accompanied by quite an extraordinary drumming.\n<ref name=\"Metaconciencia\">Bestiario. [http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/6754384/a/Bestiario.htm Metaconciencia] ''Musea Records'', France, 2003.</ref><ref name=\"Metaconciencia2003\">Bestiario. [http://www.progressor.net/review/metaconciencia_2003.html Detailed Reviews] ''Progressor'', Uzbekistan, 2003.</ref>\n\n===Spain/London===\n[[Image:Machinations of Joy.jpg|thumb|150px|left|[[Machinations of Joy (album)|Machinations of Joy]] with Dave Tucker]]Since 2007, based in Barcelona, he played as drummer and percussionist with the [[FOCO Orchestra]] of Madrid. An active member of the [[Collective of Spanish improvisers]] [[Musicalibre]] and the [[FOCO Orchestra]]. Guest of London Improvisers Orchestra (2008\u20132009) in the 10th Anniversary of LIO and in Freedom of the City Festival at Conway Hall (voice/electronics).\n\nIn the edition of the Festival [[Hurta Cordel]], celebrated the last week of January 2009, FOCO was conducted by New York experimental jazz composer& musician, William Parker, and they present together in the Palau de la Musica Catalana in Barcelona.<ref name=\"WilliamParker\">FOCO Orchestra [http://www.elperiodico.com/default.asp?idpublicacio_PK=46&idioma=CAS&idnoticia_PK=584811&idseccio_PK=1013 William Parker] ''El Peri\u00f3dico'', Palau de la Musica, 2009.</ref> In 2010 the conductor was the improviser legend, Keith Tippett.\n\n===Berlin===\n\n[[Edu Comelles]]<ref name=\"Edu Comelles\">[[Edu Comelles]][http://www.educomelles.com/] Sound Artist</ref> ( Coordinator and Creator of [[Audiotalaia]] )<ref name=\"Audiotalaia\">[[Audiotalaia]] [http://www.audiotalaia.net/home.html Audioatalaia Netlabel]</ref>  a Catalan Sound Artist living in [[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]], and Julian Bonequi ( Project manager and curator ) living since 2010 in Berlin. They decided to create '''[[Audition Records]]'''.<ref name=\"Audition Records\">[[Audition Records]][http://www.auditions.com/home.html] About Audition Records</ref> Audition Records documents the development of Improvisation in Europe by both native musicians and international ones who have settled here\u2014 musicians whose curiosity extends their sonority concepts all over the world.\n\nJulian Bonequi, resident artist at [[NK Projekt]] in 2010,<ref name=\"NK, Sound Arts, Berlin\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nkprojekt.de/ |title=NK |access-date=2020-02-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629190525/http://www.nkprojekt.de/ |archive-date=2019-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> an artist run independent non-profit organization that is dedicated to Sound Arts in Berlin, taking part in the creation and support of a \"culture\" with a focus on experimental music. Bonequi announced NK as new collaborator of Audition Records, and they decided together to publish selected concerts and performances in agreement with the artists.<ref name=\"Mat Pogo live at NK\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar003.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707185016/http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar003.html|url-status=dead|title=Mat Pogo|archivedate=July 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Joke Lanz live at NK\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar004.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707185157/http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar004.html|url-status=dead|title=Joke Lanz|archivedate=July 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nCurating and coordinating series in Berlin as associate curator, promoter or project manager since 2012. He was involved in the [[Ohrengala]]<ref name=\"Ohrengala\">[[Ohrengala]][http://www.auditionrecords.com/ohrengala.php] Regular experimental serie organised at Bei Roy</ref> at Bei Roy, collaborating until October 2012, in [[RAM]],<ref name=\"RAM\">[[RAM]][http://www.auditionrecords.com/ram.php] Radical Animation and Musik 2012, Audition Records-Salon Bruit</ref> Radical Animation and Musik at K77 in collaboration with [[Salon Bruit]],<ref name=\"Salon Bruit\">[[Salon Bruit]][http://salonbruit.org/artists/julian-bonequi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128102200/http://salonbruit.org/artists/julian-bonequi |date=2015-11-28 }} Julian Bonequi,  Salon Bruit</ref> and in the female soloist serie and documentary episodes in Berlin around improvised, noise and electroacoustic music and contemporary composers, started in February 2013 named [[Quota;unquota]]<ref name=\"Quota\">[[Quot;unquota]][http://www.auditionrecords.com/quota.php] Female Soloists In Berlin, Quota;Unquota</ref> co-curated by [[Philip Morris (musician)|Philip Morris]] aka Sciolist. In winter 2012 Bonequi moved again from Berlin to Mexico City, where he runs and coordinates Audition Records Berlin expanding Audition Records activities to Mexico City.<ref name=\"Audition Records Mexico\">[[Audition Records Mexico]][http://www.auditionrecords.com/mx.php] Audition Records in Mexico</ref>\n\n===Istanbul===\n\nJanuary 2011, [[Audition Records]] announced a new collaboration with re:kontruKt Istanbul Label after a recording with Korhan Futac\u0131 (voice, sax, zurna), Umut \u00c7a\u011flar (guitar), Barlas Tan \u00d6zemek (guitar) & Yasemin Mori (voice on track 4 & 5), catalogued re044: The Sun, the Moon & the Stars.<ref name=\"044: re:konstrukt\">[http://rekonstrukt.com/] re044:  The Sun, the Moon & the Stars</ref> [[Umut Caglar]] is the curator and project manager of [[re:konstrukt]]<ref name=\"re:konstrukt\">[[re:konstrukt]]{{cite web |url=http://auditionrecords.com/ar016.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707185111/http://auditionrecords.com/ar016.html |archivedate=2011-07-07 }} ar016: RE:KONSTRUKT - Istanbul. IMPROVISED MUSIC LABEL</ref> label.\n\n===Vienna===\n\nMarch 2011: New documents collected in Vienna are published in [[Audition Records]] as part from one of the strongest scenes happening in Vienna and working hard since eleven years ago in Austria. Conversations with [[Dieb13]]<ref name=\"Dieb13\">[[Dieb13]]{{cite web |url=http://auditionrecords.com/ar018.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504012635/http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar018.html |archivedate=2011-05-04 }} ar018: Dieb13 - Conversations</ref> about [[klingt.org]]<ref name=\"klingt.org\">[[klingt.org]]{{cite web |url=http://auditionrecords.com/ar019.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502140412/http://www.auditionrecords.com/ar019.html |archivedate=2011-05-02 }} ar019: klingt.org - 11th Years of Experimental Music</ref>\n\n===Krems===\n\nFrom 14 to 24 February 2011 Julian led a workshop for the 8B from the Borg Krems. There he showed the students how to work in Mudbox and what they could do in Maya. As a present he received a bottle of wine. In February 2011 Bonequi worked and lived in Krems as Resident Artist at [[Air-Krems]]:<ref name=\"Air-Krems\">[[Air-Krems]][http://www.air-krems.at/archive/2011/julian-bonequi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045402/http://www.air-krems.at/archive/2011/julian-bonequi |date=2016-03-04 }} Julian Bonequi, Artist in Residence</ref> \"... Each day we recorded 15 to 30 minutes of short improvisations, then we edited it and mixed, without overdubs. Always respecting the original improvisation and following differents rules we determined before we played...\"\n\n===Mexico City===\n\nSpring 2013. [[Audition Records]] announces  \"The Mexican Tour, 8 dates, 5 cities: Mexico City, Guanajuato, Quer\u00e9taro, Tlaxcala, Guadalajara\"<ref name=\"MoE, The Mexican Tour\">[[MoE]] [http://www.auditionrecords.com/moe.php] Splits gigs MoE/Bonequi</ref> - Splits gigs with the Norwegian rock noise trio [[MoE]],<ref name=\"MoE\">[[MoE]][http://www.conradsound.com/] Rock Noise From Norway, MoE</ref> organized by [[Audition Records]], and Bonequi coordinating the Tour Management, Logistics and Documentation and performing as soloist as previous act.<ref name=\"Bonequi, The Mexican Tour\">Julian Bonequi [http://www.auditionrecords.com/bonequi.php] Splits gigs MoE/Bonequi</ref>\n\n== Releases ==\n\n=== Improvised Music ===\n* ''[[Tabla y Cuchillo]]<ref name=\"Tabla y Cuchillo\">Tabla y Cuchillo: Ricardo Tejero, Niko Meinhold & Bonequi  [http://auditionrecords.com/rtma/archives/arm009.html] ''RTMA'', Berlin, 2012</ref> Recorded at Liegnitzer Stra\u00dfe 16, Berlin (2012)\n* ''[[Ultraspie\u00dfer]] (Extended Version)<ref name=\"Ultraspie\u00dfer\">Ultraspie\u00dfer:  Anton Maiof, Ratbag (Julian Percy) & Bonequi  [http://www.radicalmatters.com/radical.matters.cd.cdr.catalogue.asp?tp=1&c=381] ''RadicalMatters EditionsLabel'', Italy, 2012</ref> Recorded at NK Projekt, Berlin (2011)\n* ''[[Matarratas]] (Extended Version)<ref name=\"Matarratas\">Matarratas:  Ratbag (Julian Percy) & Bonequi  [http://www.radicalmatters.com/radical.matters.cd.cdr.catalogue.asp?tp=1&c=380] ''RadicalMatters 