 morales et politiques'' on Aristotle's ''Metaphysics'' and its historical reception, with a dissertation - ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' - that he would later publish in a revised and expanded form as ''Essai sur la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' [Volume 1] (1837).<ref name=\"SinclairBI-7\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 7</ref> See also Sinclair 'Introduction' in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-2-3\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 2-3</ref>\n* '''b''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_a}} Sinclair in ''Being Inclined'': 'Long sections of' ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' 'with the original pagination in the margins, are published in R. Belay and C. Marin, ''De la nature \u00e0 l\u2019esprit'' (Paris: ENS Editions, 2001), 201\u201313.'<ref name=\"SinclairBI-xi\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. xi</ref>\n* '''c''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_c}} Revised and expanded version of Ravaisson's 1834 prize winning essay ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-7\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 7</ref>\n* '''d''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_d}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-6\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 6</ref>\n* '''e''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_e}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-xi\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. xi</ref>\n* '''f''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_f}} See Sinclair's ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref>\n* '''g''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_g}} As well as translating the text, Carlisle and Sinclair also included two extensive supplements by way of an \"Editors\u2019 Introduction\" and \"Editors\u2019 Commentary\".<ref name=\"Carlisle&Sinclair-1-21&78-114\">\"Carlisle & Sinclair (2008), pp. 1-21; 78-114</ref> In addition, there is a long preface from Catherine Malabou titled \"Addiction and Grace\".\n* '''h''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_h}} This publication is a bilingual edition of the text and presents both ''De l\u2019habitude'' and the translation by Carlisle and Sinclair (''Of Habit'') on facing pages of the book. The French version is the Alcan edition of 1933.<ref name=\"Carlisle&Sinclair-20\">\"Carlisle & Sinclair (2008), p. 20</ref>\n* '''i''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_i}} Sinclair writes that the translation has been modified since the original translation by Carlisle and himself a few years earlier in F\u00e9lix Ravaisson ''Of Habit'' (London/New York: Continuum, 2008).<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref>\n* '''j''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_j}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-6\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 6</ref>\n* '''k''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_k}} Translated as ''La doctrine de Speusippe sur les premiers principes selon le t\u00e9moignage d'Aristote'' in ''Cahiers Philosophiques'' (n\u00b0129, 2\u00e8me trimestre), 2012; pp. 68\u201396. Translation by Alain Petit, preceded by an introduction from Petit titled \"Le sympt\u00f4me Speusippe: le spectre de l\u2019\u00e9manatisme dans la pens\u00e9e m\u00e9taphysique de Ravaisson\" (2012).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cairn.info/revue-cahiers-philosophiques1-2012-2-page-68.htm#|title=Ravaisson, la doctrine de Speusippe sur les premiers principes selon le t\u00e9moignage d'Aristote|publisher=Cahiers Philosophiques|date=2012|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n* '''l''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_l}} See also Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-8-9\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 8-9</ref>\n* '''m''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_m}} See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-3-4\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 3-4</ref> Sinclair points out that this second volume developed (but did not repeat) work from his 1834 prize winning essay ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' (1834) which had been revised and expanded in volume one (1837). Sinclair also mentions that a third and fourth volume were planned, but never came to fruition. In a footnote, however, Sinclair continues that Charles Devivaise 'published some of Ravaisson's work towards the third volume as ''Essai sur la Metaphysique d'Aristote: Fragments du Tome III'' (Paris: Vrin, 1953)'.<ref name=\"SinclairI-25\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 25</ref> \n* '''n''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_n}} This published text originally appeared as \"Rapport address\u00e9 \u00e0 M. le ministre de l\u2019Instruction publique et des cultes\" (28 December 1853).<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref> See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-11-12\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 11-12</ref> \n* '''o''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_o}} This translation is of the first 'untitled' segment of the text.<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref> In a footnote, Sinclair writes: 'For reasons of economy, I follow Dominique Janicaud in ''L'Art et les myst\u00e8res grecs'' (Paris: L'Herne, 1985) in producing just the first section of the report, but I alter his title ''L'Art et le dessin d'apr\u00e8s L\u00e9onard da Vinci''.'<ref name=\"SinclairI-27\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 27</ref>\n* '''p''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_p}} Original version presented as a paper to the Acad\u00e9mie des Insciptions et Belle-Lettres in 1849 then 1851; this version extended for publication. See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-10-11\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 10-11</ref> Published in 1856 with a cover date of 1877.<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref><ref name=\"SinclairI-11\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 11</ref>\n* '''q''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_q}} See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-13-15\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 13-15</ref>\n* '''r''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_r}} The first of two versions, the second reworked edition published in 1892. See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-15-18\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 15-18</ref>\n* '''s''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_s}} Publication details.<ref name=\"SinclairI-28\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 28</ref>\n* '''t''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_t}} Originally written in 1854, and not published for 20 years. See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-12-13\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 12-13</ref> Sinclair also has a footnote with further details.<ref name=\"SinclairI-27\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 27</ref> \n* '''u''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_u}} See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-18\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 18</ref>\n* '''v''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_v}} This article was one of several that appeared under the heading \"Dessin\"; the volume was edited by Ferdinand Buisson.<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref><ref name=\"SinclairI-12\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 12</ref>\n* '''w''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_w}} See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-11-12\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 11-12</ref>\n* '''x''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_x}} See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-19-20\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 19-20</ref>\n* '''y''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_y}} See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-18-19\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 18-19</ref>\n* '''z''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_z}} The second of two versions, the first edition was published in 1871, and was subsequently reworked in this much later publication. See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-15-18\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 15-18</ref>\n* '''aa''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_aa}} The translation here is only part of the original article, the third and final section (pp. 188-256).<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref> \n* '''bb''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_bb}} Specially commissioned lead essay for the first issue of the journal.<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref> See Sinclair's commentary in \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-20-21\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 20-21</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n'''General: Primary'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*'''Sinclair, Mark'''. ''Being Inclined: F\u00e9lix Ravaisson\u2019s Philosophy of Habit'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2019)\n{{refend}}\n\n\n'''General: Secondary'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*'''Carlisle, Clare'''. \"Between Freedom and Necessity: F\u00e9lix Ravaisson on Habit and the Moral Life\", in ''Inquiry'' (43/2: 2010), pp. 123\u201345\n*'''Carlisle, Clare and Mark Sinclair'''. \"Editors\u2019 Introduction\" and \"Editors\u2019 Commentary\" in F\u00e9lix Ravaisson ''Of Habit'', translation, introduction, and commentary by Clare Carlisle and Mark Sinclair (London/New York: Continuum, 2008), pp. 1-21; 78-114 \n*'''Grosz, Elizabeth'''. \"Habit Today: Ravaisson, Bergson, Deleuze and Us\", in ''Body and Society'' (19/2\u20133: 2013), pp. 217\u201339\n*'''Malabou, Catherine'''. \"Addiction and Grace: Preface to F\u00e9lix Ravaisson\u2019s ''Of Habit''\" in F\u00e9lix Ravaisson ''Of Habit'', translation, introduction, and commentary by Clare Carlisle and Mark Sinclair (London/New York: Continuum, 2008), pp. vii-xx \n*'''Sinclair, Mark'''. \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays'', edited by Mark Sinclair; translated by Jeremy Dunham, Adi Efal, Mark Sinclair, Tullio Viola (London: Bloomsbury, 2016), pp. 1-29\n{{refend}}\n\n\n'''Specific'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ravaisson-Mollien, Felix}}\n[[Category:1813 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:French archaeologists]]\n[[Category:French philosophers]]\n[[Category:People from Namur (city)]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n[[Category:Aristotelian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\n", "name_user": "McrPhilosophy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:improving bibliography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%A9lix_Ravaisson-Mollien"}
{"title_page": "Jeff Sarwer", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian chess player}}\n{{Infobox chess player\n|name = Jeff Sarwer\n|image= JeffSarwer.jpg\n|caption= Jeff Sarwer, [[Canada Day]], 1988\n|birthname = Jeffrey William Sarwer\n|speaks = English, French, Dutch, German, Polish, and a little Finnish\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1978|5|14}}\n|birth_place = [[Kingston, Ontario]], Canada\n|worldchampion = Boys under 10, Puerto Rico, 1986 \n}}\n\n'''Jeffrey William Sarwer''' (born May 14, 1978) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[Finland|Finnish]] ([[dual citizenship]]) former child [[chess prodigy]] whose charismatic personality and chess talent made him a well-known media figure. His chess career and his family's unconventional lifestyle were the subjects of many articles and TV shows.<ref>http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessuser?user=jeff+sarwer</ref>\n\nSarwer's attacking playing style was often compared to [[Bobby Fischer]], and a tournament game drawn against him by another young chess player, [[Joshua Waitzkin]], was the inspiration for the climax in the film ''[[Searching for Bobby Fischer]]''.\n\nSarwer won the under-10 [[World Youth Chess Championship]] in Puerto Rico in 1986 representing Canada.\n\nWhen Sarwer was 8, he was believed by many to be one of the strongest prodigies in the history of the game. [[Allen Kaufman]], head of the American Chess Foundation, said, \"Jeff at 9 is stronger than Bobby was at 11.\"  [[Bruce Pandolfini]] said, \"Of the several thousand kids I've taught, Jeff is certainly the most amazing young player I've ever seen.\"\n\n== Early career ==\nBorn in [[Kingston, Ontario]] to a [[Finns|Finnish]] mother and a Canadian father,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140112101607/http://www.pokerista.net/puoliksi-suomalainen-jeff-sarwer-shakkia-ja-pokeria/ Puoliksi suomalainen Jeff Sarwer \u2013 shakkia ja pokeria] (archived) {{in lang|fi}} Pokerista</ref> Sarwer learned the rules of [[chess]] at the age of 4 from his 6-year-old sister, Julia, and at age of 6 started to play at the [[Manhattan Chess Club]], which was one of the most prestigious chess clubs in the world at the time. [[Bruce Pandolfini]] was the manager of the club, and being impressed with them gave him and his sister free life memberships, which were usually reserved for grandmasters.\n\nSarwer used to entertain large crowds by playing 40 people at the same time known as [[Simultaneous exhibition|simultaneous chess]], every [[Canada Day]] from the age of 7 on [[Parliament Hill]] in [[Ottawa]]. He also used to show up and play [[Fast chess|speed chess]] at Washington Square Park in New York City, where large numbers of people gathered to watch his games.\n\n== Media life ==\nAt the age of 7, Sarwer\n's enthusiasm for the game caught the attention of Grandmaster [[Edmar Mednis]] and he invited him to analyze the 1986 World Championship Match between Kasparov-Karpov on PBS. Sarwer and his sister Julia (who was also a world champion for girls under 10) continued to do this for the rematch in 1987 as well. After this Jeff and Julia became well known in media circles and appeared on various talk shows and were the subject of a documentary.\n\nMagazines such as ''[[GQ]]'' and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' wrote articles about Sarwer and his family, often highlighting their bizarre lifestyle and questioning his safety and chess career under his father's care.\n\n== ''Vanity Fair'' article ==\nJeff's father did not allow him to continue his chess career when it became apparent that he would not be able to keep full control over Jeff's life. He moved the family away from New York City and ran into trouble with The Children's Aid Society of Ontario. A featured article in ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' magazine by [[John Colapinto]] detailed child abuse of Jeff and Julia and prompted the C.A.S. to take him and his sister into protective custody.\n\nJeff and Julia ran away from the C.A.S. back to their father and hid out from authorities in order to not be taken away into custody again. The Sarwers lived in various countries and got used to living an anonymous lifestyle.\n\n== ''Searching For Bobby Fischer'' ==\n{{algebraic notation|pos=secright}}\nIn 1993 the film ''[[Searching for Bobby Fischer]]'' was released and Jeff Sarwer's character was portrayed as \"Jonathan Poe\". In the film's final game, Poe declined the [[draw by agreement|offer]] of a [[draw (chess)|draw]] and eventually lost. In reality, Sarwer declined the draw offer by Josh Waitzkin, but the game ended in a draw (because of insufficient material) a few moves later. Under tournament [[Tie-breaking in Swiss-system tournaments|tie-breaking rules]], Waitzkin was determined to have played more challenging opponents during the overall competition and was awarded first place, but they were declared US Primary School co-champions.  At the time that the game was played, Sarwer was 7 and Waitzkin 9 years old.\n\n:Sarwer vs. Waitzkin, 1986 <br />1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 d6 5.f4 0-0 6.Nf3 Nbd7 7.e5 Ne8 8.Bd3 c5 9.dxc5 Nxc5 10.Bc2 a5 11.0-0 b6 12.Be3 Bb7 13.Qd4 dxe5 14.Nxe5 Qxd4 15.Bxd4 Rd8 16.Bxc5 bxc5 17.Na4 Bxe5 18.fxe5 Rd2 19.Rf2 Rxf2 20.Kxf2 f6 21.e6 Nd6 22.Nxc5 Rc8 23.Nxb7 Nxb7 24.b3 Nc5 25.Re1 Rc6 26.Be4 Ra6 27.Bc2 Rxe6 28.Rxe6 Nxe6 29.Ke3 Kf8 30.Ke4 Ke8 31.g3 Kd7 32.Kd5 f5 33.a3 h6 34.b4 axb4 35.axb4 Nc7+ 36.Kc5 e5 37.Ba4+ Kc8 38.Bc6 e4 39.b5 e3 40.Bf3 Ne6+ 41.Kd5 Ng5 42.Be2 Kc7 43.Ke5 Ne4 44.Kd4 Kd6 45.Kxe3 Kc5 46.g4 Nd6 47.Kf4 g5+ 48.Ke5 fxg4 49.Kf6 g3 50.hxg3 Ne4+ 51.Kg6 Nxg3 52.Bd3 Nh1 53.Kxh6 g4 54.Kg5 g3 55.Be4 Nf2 56.Bd5 Nd1 57.Kf4 Nc3 58.Bc6 Ne2+ 59.Kf3 Nd4+ 60.Kxg3 Nxc6 61.bxc6 Kxc6 62.Kf3 Kc5 63.Ke3 Kxc4 \u00bd\u2013\u00bd<ref>[http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1473029 Sarwer vs. Waitzkin] [[Chessgames.com]]</ref>\n\n== Resurfacing ==\nAfter he disappeared at a very young age, many people thought Sarwer would not be seen playing chess again. In September 2007 he resurfaced to the chess scene, apparently without training and entered a 30-minute [[rapid chess|semi-rapid]] tournament at Malbork castle in Poland. He finished in third place with a score of 7/9 in a group of 86 players including four grandmasters.  Since he had no active chess rating, he was given a provisional [[Elo rating system|Elo rating]] of 2250 [[FIDE]] but seemed to perform above that level. In January 2010 Sarwer gave a long interview to ''Chess Life Online'' detailing his experiences from that tournament and talking about his current life in Europe. In August 2010, Sarwer was profiled in the ''Sunday Times Magazine'' talking about his father's methods, his chess career and his reappearance in public.  Sarwer says that if he decided to make chess a priority, he would do so to become a grandmaster.  \"It would require at least two years of dedicated hardcore study and practice,\" he said, \"especially in regards to opening preparation\" for him to achieve that goal.<ref name = \"cardplayer\" />\n\nIn summer 2015 Sarwer participated in VI Shakkinet tournament in Finland.<ref>http://www.chess-results.com/tnr176452.aspx?lan=18&art=4&wi=821</ref> Sarwer scored 5/9, which was enough for IM-norm.\n\n== Poker ==\nSince December 2008, Sarwer has been playing on the [[European Poker Tour]].<ref name=JBet>{{cite web|title=All The Faces Of Jeff Sarwer|url=http://www.johnnybet.com/all-the-faces-of-jeff-sarwer|website=JohnnyBet.com|accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref> He has had two final table appearances and earned about $500,000.<ref name = \"cardplayer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cardplayer.com/poker-news/10384-a-poker-life-jeff-sarwer|title= A Poker Life -- Jeff Sarwer: Former Chess Prodigy Tells His Extraordinary Story|last=Pempus|first=Brian|publisher=Cardplayer Magazine|date= December 19, 2010|accessdate=December 20, 2010|work=Cardplayer.com}}</ref> In February 2010, ''[[Bluff (magazine)#Bluff Europe magazine|Bluff Europe]]'' magazine ran a featured article about him and his new poker career.<ref name =\"bluff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bluffeurope.com/interview/en/The-next-big-thing-Jeff-Sarwer-by-Stephen-Bartley_6594.aspx|title= The next big thing: Jeff Sarwer|last=Bartley|first=Stephen|publisher=Bluff Europe Magazine|date= February 3, 2010|accessdate=December 25, 2010|work=BluffEurope.com}}</ref>  He is represented by the player agency Poker Icons.\n\n== Radio interview ==\nSarwer was the subject of [[BBC World Service]]'s programme''[[The Interview (BBC World Service Radio Programme)|The Interview]]'' on December 19, 2010, in which he candidly recounted his life and his childhood experiences and his relationship with his abusive father. He also spoke of successful years in United States real estate in his 20s and his current success on the professional poker circuit in Europe in his 30s.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00cdz33</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Jeff Sarwer}}\n* [http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessplayer?pid=81835 chessgames.com profile]\n* [http://pokerdb.thehendonmob.com/player.php?a=r&n=116914 The Hendon Mob Poker Database]\n* [http://main.uschess.org/content/view/10007/571/ Chess Life article]\n* [http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/Magazine/Features/article352062.ece Sunday Times Magazine article (subscription required)\n* [http://www.bluffeurope.com/interview/en/The-next-big-thing-Jeff-Sarwer-_6594.aspx/ Bluff Magazine article]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5-Wgv3rn6A8 Biography video of Jeff Sarwer Part 1]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ycMAZeGFNW4 Biography video of Jeff Sarwer Part 2]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarwer, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian chess players]]\n[[Category:Canadian poker players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kingston, Ontario]]\n[[Category:World Youth Chess Champions]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Finnish descent]]\n[[Category:Finnish people of Canadian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian chess player}}\n{{Infobox chess player\n|name = Jeff Sarwer\n|image= JeffSarwer.jpg\n|caption= Jeff Sarwer, [[Canada Day]], 1988\n|birthname = Jeffrey William Sarwer\n|speaks = English, French, Dutch, German, Polish, and a little Finnish\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1978|5|14}}\n|birth_place = [[Kingston, Ontario]], Canada\n|worldchampion = Boys under 10, Puerto Rico, 1986 \n}}\n\n'''Jeff Sarwer''' (born May 14, 1978) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[Finland|Finnish]] ([[dual citizenship]]) former child [[chess prodigy]] whose charismatic personality and chess talent made him a well-known media figure. His chess career and his family's unconventional lifestyle were the subjects of many articles and TV shows.<ref>http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessuser?user=jeff+sarwer</ref>\n\nSarwer's attacking playing style was often compared to [[Bobby Fischer]], and a tournament game drawn against him by another young chess player, [[Joshua Waitzkin]], was the inspiration for the climax in the film ''[[Searching for Bobby Fischer]]''.\n\nSarwer won the under-10 [[World Youth Chess Championship]] in Puerto Rico in 1986 representing Canada.\n\nWhen Sarwer was 8, he was believed by many to be one of the strongest prodigies in the history of the game. [[Allen Kaufman]], head of the American Chess Foundation, said, \"Jeff at 9 is stronger than Bobby was at 11.\"  [[Bruce Pandolfini]] said, \"Of the several thousand kids I've taught, Jeff is certainly the most amazing young player I've ever seen.\"\n\n== Early career ==\nBorn in [[Kingston, Ontario]] to a [[Finns|Finnish]] mother and a Canadian father,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140112101607/http://www.pokerista.net/puoliksi-suomalainen-jeff-sarwer-shakkia-ja-pokeria/ Puoliksi suomalainen Jeff Sarwer \u2013 shakkia ja pokeria] (archived) {{in lang|fi}} Pokerista</ref> Sarwer learned the rules of [[chess]] at the age of 4 from his 6-year-old sister, Julia, and at age of 6 started to play at the [[Manhatta