omparative study |location=New Delhi|publisher=Orient Longman |isbn=978-8125022985 }}\n* Jenny Taylor, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/sep/08/religion-islam-tablighi-jamaat What is the Tablighi Jamaat?], The Guardian, 8 September 2009.\n* {{Cite journal |last=Stern |first=Jessica |title=Pakistan's Jihad Culture. |journal=Foreign Affairs |volume=79 |issue=6 |pages=115\u201326 |year=2000 |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/asia/2000-11-01/pakistans-jihad-culture |doi=10.2307/20049971 |jstor=20049971 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.delhimarkaz.com/?m=1/ Tablighi Jamaat Official Website]\n{{Tablighi Jamaat}}\n{{IslamismSA|state=collapse}}\n\n{{Coord|31|15|25|N|74|13|22|E|display=title|region:PK_type:city(31592)_source:dewiki}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1927 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Tablighi Jamaat|*]]\n[[Category:Islamic organisations based in India]]\n[[Category:Sunni Islamist groups]]\n[[Category:Islamic organizations established in 1926]]\n[[Category:Deobandi]]\n", "name_user": "Quuxplusone", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrigin:remove fragment inserted at the top of this section \u2014 that website isn't directly relevant to this article, and the exhortation is inappropriate for Wikipedia", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablighi_Jamaat"}
{"title_page": "SS Mona's Isle (1905)", "text_new": "{{Other ships|Mona's Isle (disambiguation){{!}}Mona's Isle}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image =[[File:Mona's Isle.JPG|300px|Mona's Isle]]\n| Ship caption = ''Mona's Isle''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header =\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|civil}} {{shipboxflag|Isle of Man|civil}}\n| Ship name =*1905: ''Onward''\n*1920: ''Mona's Isle''\n| Ship owner =*1905\u20131920: South Eastern and Chatham Railway Company\n*1920\u20131948: [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]].\n| Ship operator =*1905\u20131920: South Eastern and Chatham Railway Company\n*1920\u20131948: IoMSPCo.\n| Ship registry = [[Douglas, Isle of Man]]\n| Ship route = 1905\u20131918: [[Folkestone]]\u2013[[Boulogne]]\n1920\u20131948: Mainly summer routes from [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]]\u2013[[Dublin]]/[[Belfast]].\n| Ship ordered =\n| Ship builder = [[William Denny and Brothers]], [[Dumbarton]]\n| Ship original cost =\n| Ship yard number = \n| Ship way number =\n| Ship laid down = 1905\n| Ship launched =\n| Ship completed =\n| Ship christened =\n| Ship acquired =\n| Ship maiden voyage =\n| Ship in service = 1905\n| Ship out of service = 1948\n| Ship identification =*[[Official number|Official Number 125122]]\n*Code Letters\n*H C M E\n*{{ICS|Hotel}}{{ICS|Charlie}}{{ICS|Mike}}{{ICS|Echo}}\n*G F P M\n*{{ICS|Golf}}{{ICS|Foxtrot}}{{ICS|Papa}}{{ICS|Mike}}\n*<ref>Ships of the Isle of Man Steam Packet Company (Fred Henry) p.66</ref>\n| Ship fate = Scrapped at [[Milford Haven]] 1948\n| Ship status =Scrapped\n| Ship notes =\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header =\n| Header caption =\n| Ship type = [[Packet trade|Packet Steamer]]\n| Ship tonnage = {{GRT|1691|disp=long}}\n| Ship displacement =\n| Ship length = {{convert|311|ft|2|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|40|ft|1|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draught =\n| Ship depth ={{convert|16|ft|6|in|m|1|abbr=on}} \n| Ship decks =\n| Ship deck clearance =\n| Ship ramps =\n| Ship power = {{convert|7500|shp|lk=in|abbr=on}} \n| Ship propulsion = Screw\n| Ship speed = {{convert|22|kn|km/h}}\n| Ship capacity = 1,479 passengers\n| Ship crew = 70\n| Ship notes =\n}}\n|}\n\n'''SS [[Royal Mail Ship|(RMS)]] ''Mona's Isle'' (IV)''' was a steel, triple-screw turbine driven [[packet steamer]] operated by the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]] between 1920 and 1948. Built in 1905 for the South Eastern & Chatham Railway Company, she was operated as '''''Onward''''' between [[Folkestone]] and [[Boulogne]]. In 1918 a fire was only controlled by scuttling the vessel. She was righted and in 1920, the hull was purchased by IOMSPCo to replace tonnage lost during the war. She was the first ship to complete a round trip during the evacuation of Dunkirk ([[Operation Dynamo]]), rescuing a total of 2,634 troops.\n\n==Construction & dimensions==\n''Onward'' was built at [[William Denny and Brothers]] shipyard on the [[River Leven, Dunbartonshire|River Leven]] adjoining the [[River Clyde]] at [[Dumbarton]], in 1905. She was a steel, triple-screw turbine driven vessel built for the [[South Eastern and Chatham Railway]] for their [[Folkestone]]&ndash;[[Boulogne]] route.<ref name=\"simpleon\">{{cite web| url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/SR_SECR1.html#anchor1549039| title=Onward| publisher=Simpleon Postcards| accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nLength 311'2\"; beam 40'1\"; depth 16'6\". ''Onward'' had accommodation for a crew of 70, and was certificated to carry 1,479 passengers. Her engines developed 7,500 i.h.p. which gave her a service speed of 22 knots.\n\n==Service==\n\n===South Eastern & Chatham Railway===\n''Omward'' was primarily used on the [[Folkestone]]\u2013[[Boulogne]] service.\n\n[[File:SS Onward, 1914..JPG|thumb|left|''Onward'' pictured at [[Boulogne]], 1914.]]\n\nHer most prestigious passenger during her cross-channel service was His Majesty [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]] who crossed from [[Dover]] to [[Calais]] onboard ''Onward'' on 4 May 1905.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://freespace.virgin.net/jack.lee2000/onwardimg.htm| publisher=Paddle Steamer Picture Gallery| title=TS Onward (Mona's Isle (IV))| accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June 1908, ''Onward'' was involved in a head-on collision with the steamer {{ship|TSS|The Queen||2}},<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/services/archives/exhibitions/ernestarthurbinstead/photogallery/sketchbook21908/ssonward/| title=SS Onward| publisher=University of Glasgow Archives| accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> killing the bow lookout man. Following the collision, ''Onward'' returned to Folkestone, and from there to [[William Denny and Brothers]], Dumbarton, where she underwent repairs which kept her out of service for a month.<ref name=\"ebay.com\">{{cite web| url=http://www.ebay.com/itm/1465s-EARLY-1900-POSTCARD-OF-THE-S-S-ONWARD-LEAVING-FOLKESTONE-HARBOUR/261265474812?_trksid=p2047675.m1850&_trkparms=aid%3D222002%26algo%3DSIC.FIT%26ao%3D1%26asc%3D11%26meid%3D964011154046183029%26pid%3D100011%26prg%3D1005%26rk%3D1%26rkt%3D5%26sd%3D251256346549%26\n| title=Early 1900 Postcard of the S.S. Onward leaving Folkestone Harbour| publisher=eBay| accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nUpon the completion of repairs, ''Onward'' had the distinction of carrying the very first motor car across the [[English Channel]].<ref name=\"ebay.com\"/>\n\n===First World War===\nUnder her original owners, the vessel saw service in World War I. Primarily, she was used as a troop transport ship for the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War I)|British Expeditionary Force]], on her regular route between [[Folkestone]] and [[Boulogne]].\n\nOn 24 September 1918, she caught fire in [[Folkestone Harbour]]. The fire took hold, and was only contained by the opening of her [[seacock]]s in order to prevent the pier catching fire.<ref name=\"theremembranceline.org.uk\">{{cite web| url=http://www.theremembranceline.org.uk/past_trains.htm| title=The Trains| publisher=The Remembrance Line| accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> This resulted in the [[scuttling]] of the vessel; she turned over onto her port side, and was subsequently hauled upright by a team of five steam locomotives in harness.<ref name=\"theremembranceline.org.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.warrenpress.net/FolkestoneThenNow/FolkestoneFerries.html| title=The Ferries| publisher=Folkestone Then and Now| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Onward scuttled at Folkestone Harbour..JPG|thumb|left|An aerial view of ''Onward'' lying on her [[Port and starboard|portside]], after being [[Scuttling|scuttled]] in [[Folkestone Harbour]], September, 1918. Note the [[Dazzle camouflage|dazzle camouflage paint scheme]], said to provide a degree of protection against U-boat attacks.]]\n\nThe hull of ''Onward'' was purchased by the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]] in 1920 and rebuilt as ''Mona's Isle'',<ref name=\"simpleon\"/> the fourth ship in the company's history to be so named.\n\n===Isle of Man Steam Packet Company===\nOf eleven Steam Packet ships either purchased or chartered by the [[Admiralty]] during the [[Great War]], only four returned to service with the Company after the cessation of hostilities, and consequently, new ships were going to be needed to handle the resumption of peacetime traffic. However, industry as a whole was in a disorganised and seriously run-down state after the challenges of the war years, and new vessels could not be built in time for the tourist influx of 1919.\n\nThe Company compromised. Starting with the purchase of {{SS|Mona|1907|2}}, they set about redressing their wartime losses, which also saw the purchase of ''Onward'' forming part of this policy. The vessel is the only Steam Packet Company ship to carry the [[Flag of the Isle of Man|Manx flag]] down the [[River Thames]], for she was transferred to the Company when berthed at Union Dock, [[Limehouse Basin|Limehouse]], in the [[Port of London]].\n\n''Onward'' commenced Steam Packet service still under her original name, until 27 August 1920, when she was renamed ''Mona's Isle.''\n\n''Mona's Isle'' saw service to the various ports then served by the Isle of Man Steam Packet Company, but was mainly used on summer work between [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] and the company's [[Ireland|Irish]] services to [[Belfast]] and [[Dublin]]\n\nOn Monday, 29 June 1936, she struck the [[Howth Head|Devil's Rock in Balscadden Bay]], but was able to reach [[Dublin Port|Dublin]] safely.\nShe was taking on water and could not complete the return journey until repaired.\n\n===Second World War===\nThe ''Mona's Isle'' was considered an old ship, being 34 years old when war broke out in 1939. Like other Steam Packet ships, she was fitted out as an ABV \u2013 an [[Ocean boarding vessel|Armed Boarding Vessel]] \u2013 and for the first few months of the war her life was largely uneventful. This was set to change, as with the plight of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] becoming all too apparent, ''Mona's Isle'' joined no less than seven of her Steam Packet sisters, and made passage to [[Dunkirk]].\n\nAccording to [[Admiralty]] records, ''Mona's Isle'' was the first ship to leave [[Dover]] for [[Dunkirk]]<ref name=\"dynamo\">{{cite web| url=http://dkepaves.free.fr/download/operation%20_dynamo.pdf| title=Operation Dynamo \u2013 The Mass Evacuation from Dunkirk| publisher=Alan L.Putland| format=PDF| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> when [[Dunkirk evacuation|Operation Dynamo]] began, although an exception being [[HMS Wolsey|HMS ''Wolsey'']], a destroyer which was to act as a radio link ship.\n\n''Mona's Isle'' departed Dover at [[24-hour clock|21:00hrs]] on 27 May 1940.<ref name=\"dynamo\"/> The journey across the [[Strait of Dover|Channel]] during the hours of darkness was uneventful, and she arrived at Dunkirk at approximately [[24-hour clock|midnight.]] Once secured at the [[Wharf|quayside]], ''Mona's Isle'' embarked 1,420 troops<ref name=\"dynamo\"/> and she left at first light the next morning.\n\n[[File:Dunkirk Evacuation shipping routes.png|thumb|Map of the three evacuation routes]]Three routes were allocated to the evacuating vessels.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/operation_dynamo.html| title=Operation Dynamo, the evacuation from Dunkirk, 27 May-4 June 1940| author=Rickard, J| date=16 February 2008| publisher=Military History Encyclopedia on the Web| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> The shortest was '''Route Z''', a distance of 39 [[nautical miles]], which, after leaving Dunkirk followed the [[English Channel|French coast]] as far as No.6 Buoy, then turning [[Bearing (navigation)|Nor'west]] on a direct line to [[Dover]]. The longest of the three was '''Route Y''', a distance of 87 [[nautical miles]] that followed the French coast as far as Bray-Dunes then turned [[Bearing (navigation)|Nor'east]] until reaching the Kwinte Buoy.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IK8yWtpUyY0C&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=Kwinte+Buoy&source=bl&ots=rm5sPreVV9&sig=ZV-lj5Lt7ZmxN-_Uv-e1fKcIpJ4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qvt4UbSjJcXQOdusgbgP&sqi=2&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Kwinte%20Buoy&f=false| title=Dunkirk 1940: Operation Dynamo| author=Doug Dildy| author2=Howard Gerrard| publisher=Osprey Publishing| location=Oxford| year=2010| isbn=9781846034572| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> From there, after proceeding initially to the [[Bearing (navigation)|Nor'west]], ships then sailed in an westerly direction as far as the [[Goodwin Sands|North Goodwin Lightship]], then headed due south round the [[Goodwin Sands]] to Dover. The third, and although the safest from the German shore batteries, was through a heavily mined portion of the [[English Channel]]. This was '''Route X''', a distance of 55 nautical miles, and ships headed due north out of Dunkirk, through the Ruytingen Pass<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UqEOScq-AjUC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=Ruytingen+Pass&source=bl&ots=oCbRTLPOVS&sig=5hXX8eyaoX0F0j_mlBqMdGi50nA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EPV3Ud6zGYHkOrWggYgG&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Ruytingen%20Pass&f=false| title=The Evacuation from Dunkirk| author=W. J. R. Gardner| publisher=Frank Cass Publishers| year=2000| isbn=9780714651200| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> and onto the North Goodwin Lightship before heading due south round the Goodwin Sands to Dover. The combination of the minefields and sandbanks meant passage via Route X was confined to daylight hours only.\n\nReturning by Route Z, the ''Mona's Isle'' came under fire from German shore batteries from the French coast. Many shells exploded close to the ship sending plumes of white water into the air and with water spraying over the decks. A number of shells failed to explode as they hit the ship, but one fell aft and smashed the rudder. The ''Mona's Isle'' was a triple screw vessel, so by careful use of port and starboard engines, the ship was able to reach the safety of Dover, but not before a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109|Bf 109]] had strafed the ship a couple of times killing 23 and wounding 60 others. Using the same route, two coasters, the ''Sequacity'' and the ''Yewdale'' headed for Dunkirk, and along the French coast they both came in for the same treatment. ''Sequacity'' suffered two direct hits, one into her starboard side, the other into the engine room and she started to sink, the crew being rescued by the ''Yewdale'', which aborted the mission and returned to [[Dover]].\n\nHowever ''Mona's Isle'' reached Dover safely, escorted by the [[Destroyer escort|destroyer]] [[HMS Windsor (D42)|HMS ''Windsor'']].\nThe mission had taken nearly 15 hours and she was recorded as the first ship to complete a round trip during the evacuation.<ref name=\"dynamo\"/>\n\nTwo awards were later made to members of the [[ship's company]] or their part in the action. The Commanding Officer, [[Commander|Cdr]] [[John Dowding (naval officer)|J.C.K. Dowding]] [[Royal Naval Reserve|RNR]], received the [[Distinguished Service Order]]. [[Petty Officer]] L.B. Kearley-Pope, [[Royal Naval Reserve|RNR]], was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Medal (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Medal]]. He had remained at a 12-pounder gun despite multiple wounds and he took a great risk in coming out of cover to close the [[cordite]] boxes. There were casualties among the gun's crew, but the PO continued to carry out his duties until the ship berthed six hours later. Cdr Dowding was later promoted to [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Captain]]. He was [[Commodore (rank)|Commodore]] of the ill-fated [[Convoy PQ 17]] to Russia, which was forced to scatter and suffered heavy losses in July 1942.\n\n''Mona's Isle'' made a second round trip to Dunkirk, bringing out a further 1,200 troops, and bringing her total to 2,634. The rest of her war service was spent either as an [[Ocean boarding vessel|Armoured Boarding Vessel]] or an accommodation ship. She was transferred to the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] in 1941, where she was three times involved in collisions, one of which did extensive damage and sent her to [[Drydock|dock]] for three months.\n\nOnce on the Tyne, where she lent support to the [[Anti-aircraft warfare|AA]] defences of coastal convoys, ''Mona's Isle'' gave valuable assistance on two occasions to [[Cargo ship|merchantmen]] that had been bombed, in one case rescuing 32 survivors. After [[D-Day]] she worked on cross-Channel transport duties until June 1945, when she was then chartered by the Ministry of War Transport before she was finally released from her war service in March 1946.\n\n===Post-war===\nAfter her war service, ''Mona's Isle'' returned to her duties within the Steam Packet fleet. She worked for a further two years, until with the introduction of the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company#The \"Six Sisters\"|\"Six Sisters\"]], she was withdrawn from service.\n\nAfter a thoroughly eventful life spanning 43 years, ''Mona's Isle'' was broken up at [[Milford Haven]] in 1948.\n\n==Gallery==\n\n{{gallery\n|title= RMS ''Mona's Isle''\n|width=250 | height=170 | lines=3\n|align=centre\n|image:Mona's Isle in the Mersey..JPG|''Mona's Isle'' in the [[River Mersey|Mersey]]\n|image:Mona's Isle enters Douglas Harbour..JPG|''Mona's Isle'' enters [[Douglas Harbour]]\n|image:Mona's Isle and Victoria.jpg|[[SS Victoria (1907)|''Victoria'']] (left) and ''Mona's Isle'' (right), during their winter lay-up at the Tongue, [[Douglas, Isle of Man]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* Chappell, Connery (1980). ''Island Lifeline'' T.Stephenson & Sons Ltd {{ISBN|0-901314-20-X}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Steam Packet Ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mona's Isle (1905)}}\n[[Category:Ships of the Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]]\n[[Category:1905 ships]]\n[[Category:1948 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:Steamships]]\n[[Category:Steamships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:World War I merchant ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:World War I merchant ships of the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Ferries of the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:World War II merchant ships of the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:World War II merchant ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Merchant ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Clyde]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other ships|Mona's Isle (disambiguation){{!}}Mona's Isle}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image =[[File:Mona's Isle.JPG|300px|Mona's Isle]]\n| Ship caption = ''Mona's Isle''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header =\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|civil}} {{shipboxflag|Isle of Man|civil}}\n| Ship name =*1905: ''Onward''\n*1920: ''Mona's Isle''\n| Ship owner =*1905\u20131920: South Eastern and Chatham Railway Company\n*1920\u20131948: [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]].\n| Ship operator =*1905\u20131920: South Eastern and Chatham Railway Company\n*1920\u20131948: IoMSPCo.\n| Ship registry = [[Douglas, Isle of Man]]\n| Ship route = 1905\u20131918: [[Folkestone]]\u2013[[Boulogne]]\n1920\u20131948: Mainly summer routes from [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]]\u2013[[Dublin]]/[[Belfast]].\n| Ship ordered =\n| Ship builder = [[William Denny and Brothers]], [[Dumbarton]]\n| Ship original cost =\n| Ship yard number = \n| Ship way number =\n| Ship laid down = 1905\n| Ship launched =\n| Ship completed =\n| Ship christened =\n| Ship acquired =\n| Ship maiden voyage =\n| Ship in service = 1905\n| Ship out of service = 1948\n| Ship identification =*[[Official number|Official Number 125122]]\n*Code Letters\n*H C M E\n*{{ICS|Hotel}}{{ICS|Charlie}}{{ICS|Mike}}{{ICS|Echo}}\n*G F P M\n*{{ICS|Golf}}{{ICS|Foxtrot}}{{ICS|Papa}}{{ICS|Mike}}\n*<ref>Ships of the Isle of Man Steam Packet Company (Fred Henry) p.66</ref>\n| Ship fate = Scrapped at [[Milford Haven]] 1948\n| Ship status =Srapped\n| Ship notes =\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header =\n| Header caption =\n| Ship type = [[Packet trade|Packet Steamer]]\n| Ship tonnage = {{GRT|1691|disp=long}}\n| Ship displacement =\n| Ship length = {{convert|311|ft|2|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|40|ft|1|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draught =\n| Ship depth ={{convert|16|ft|6|in|m|1|abbr=on}} \n| Ship decks =\n| Ship deck clearance =\n| Ship ramps =\n| Ship power = {{convert|7500|shp|lk=in|abbr=on}} \n| Ship propulsion = Screw\n| Ship speed = {{convert|22|kn|km/h}}\n| Ship capacity = 1,479 passengers\n| Ship crew = 70\n| Ship notes =\n}}\n|}\n\n'''SS [[Royal Mail Ship|(RMS)]] ''Mona's Isle'' (IV)''' was a steel, triple-screw turbine driven [[packet steamer]] operated by the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]] between 1920 and 1948. Built in 1905 for the South Eastern & Chatham Railway Company, she was operated as '''''Onward''''' between [[Folkestone]] and [[Boulogne]]. In 1918 a fire was only controlled by scuttling the vessel. She was righted and in 1920, the hull was purchased by IOMSPCo to replace tonnage lost during the war. She was the first ship to complete a round trip during the evacuation of Dunkirk ([[Operation Dynamo]]), rescuing a total of 2,634 troops.\n\n==Construction & dimensions==\n''Onward'' was built at [[William Denny and Brothers]] shipyard on the [[River Leven, Dunbartonshire|River Leven]] adjoining the [[River Clyde]] at [[Dumbarton]], in 1905. She was a steel, triple-screw turbine driven vessel built for the [[South Eastern and Chatham Railway]] for their [[Folkestone]]&ndash;[[Boulogne]] route.<ref name=\"simpleon\">{{cite web| url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/SR_SECR1.html#anchor1549039| title=Onward| publisher=Simpleon Postcards| accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nLength 311'2\"; beam 40'1\"; depth 16'6\". ''Onward'' had accommodation for a crew of 70, and was certificated to carry 1,479 passengers. Her engines developed 7,500 i.h.p. which gave her a service speed of 22 knots.\n\n==Service==\n\n===South Eastern & Chatham Railway===\n''Omward'' was primarily used on the [[Folkestone]]\u2013[[Boulogne]] service.\n\n[[File:SS Onward, 1914..JPG|thumb|left|''Onward'' pictured at [[Boulogne]], 1914.]]\n\nHer most prestigious passenger during her cross-channel service was His Majesty [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]] who crossed from [[Dover]] to [[Calais]] onboard ''Onward'' on 4 May 1905.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://freespace.virgin.net/jack.lee2000/onwardimg.htm| publisher=Paddle Steamer Picture Gallery| title=TS Onward (Mona's Isle (IV))| accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June 1908, ''Onward'' was involved in a head-on collision with the steamer {{ship|TSS|The Queen||2}},<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/services/archives/exhibitions/ernestarthurbinstead/photogallery/sketchbook21908/ssonward/| title=SS Onward| publisher=University of Glasgow Archives| accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> killing the bow lookout man. Following the collision, ''Onward'' returned to Folkestone, and from there to [[William Denny and Brothers]], Dumbarton, where she underwent repairs which kept her out of service for a month.<ref name=\"ebay.com\">{{cite web| url=http://www.ebay.com/itm/1465s-EARLY-1900-POSTCARD-OF-THE-S-S-ONWARD-LEAVING-FOLKESTONE-HARBOUR/261265474812?_trksid=p2047675.m1850&_trkparms=aid%3D222002%26algo%3DSIC.FIT%26ao%3D1%26asc%3D11%26meid%3D964011154046183029%26pid%3D100011%26prg%3D1005%26rk%3D1%26rkt%3D5%26sd%3D251256346549%26\n| title=Early 1900 Postcard of the S.S. Onward leaving Folkestone Harbour| publisher=eBay| accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nUpon the completion of repairs, ''Onward'' had the distinction of carrying the very first motor car across the [[English Channel]].<ref name=\"ebay.com\"/>\n\n===First World War===\nUnder her original owners, the vessel saw service in World War I. Primarily, she was used as a troop transport ship for the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War I)|British Expeditionary Force]], on her regular route between [[Folkestone]] and [[Boulogne]].\n\nOn 24 September 1918, she caught fire in [[Folkestone Harbour]]. The fire took hold, and was only contained by the opening of her [[seacock]]s in order to prevent the pier catching fire.<ref name=\"theremembranceline.org.uk\">{{cite web| url=http://www.theremembranceline.org.uk/past_trains.htm| title=The Trains| publisher=The Remembrance Line| accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> This resulted in the [[scuttling]] of the vessel; she turned over onto her port side, and was subsequently hauled upright by a team of five steam locomotives in harness.<ref name=\"theremembranceline.org.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.warrenpress.net/FolkestoneThenNow/FolkestoneFerries.html| title=The Ferries| publisher=Folkestone Then and Now| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Onward scuttled at Folkestone Harbour..JPG|thumb|left|An aerial view of ''Onward'' lying on her [[Port and starboard|portside]], after being [[Scuttling|scuttled]] in [[Folkestone Harbour]], September, 1918. Note the [[Dazzle camouflage|dazzle camouflage paint scheme]], said to provide a degree of protection against U-boat attacks.]]\n\nThe hull of ''Onward'' was purchased by the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]] in 1920 and rebuilt as ''Mona's Isle'',<ref name=\"simpleon\"/> the fourth ship in the company's history to be so named.\n\n===Isle of Man Steam Packet Company===\nOf eleven Steam Packet ships either purchased or chartered by the [[Admiralty]] during the [[Great War]], only four returned to service with the Company after the cessation of hostilities, and consequently, new ships were going to be needed to handle the resumption of peacetime traffic. However, industry as a whole was in a disorganised and seriously run-down state after the challenges of the war years, and new vessels could not be built in time for the tourist influx of 1919.\n\nThe Company compromised. Starting with the purchase of {{SS|Mona|1907|2}}, they set about redressing their wartime losses, which also saw the purchase of ''Onward'' forming part of this policy. The vessel is the only Steam Packet Company ship to carry the [[Flag of the Isle of Man|Manx flag]] down the [[River Thames]], for she was transferred to the Company when berthed at Union Dock, [[Limehouse Basin|Limehouse]], in the [[Port of London]].\n\n''Onward'' commenced Steam Packet service still under her original name, until 27 August 1920, when she was renamed ''Mona's Isle.''\n\n''Mona's Isle'' saw service to the various ports then served by the Isle of Man Steam Packet Company, but was mainly used on summer work between [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] and the company's [[Ireland|Irish]] services to [[Belfast]] and [[Dublin]]\n\nOn Monday, 29 June 1936, she struck the [[Howth Head|Devil's Rock in Balscadden Bay]], but was able to reach [[Dublin Port|Dublin]] safely.\nShe was taking on water and could not complete the return journey until repaired.\n\n===Second World War===\nThe ''Mona's Isle'' was considered an old ship, being 34 years old when war broke out in 1939. Like other Steam Packet ships, she was fitted out as an ABV \u2013 an [[Ocean boarding vessel|Armed Boarding Vessel]] \u2013 and for the first few months of the war her life was largely uneventful. This was set to change, as with the plight of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]] becoming all too apparent, ''Mona's Isle'' joined no less than seven of her Steam Packet sisters, and made passage to [[Dunkirk]].\n\nAccording to [[Admiralty]] records, ''Mona's Isle'' was the first ship to leave [[Dover]] for [[Dunkirk]]<ref name=\"dynamo\">{{cite web| url=http://dkepaves.free.fr/download/operation%20_dynamo.pdf| title=Operation Dynamo \u2013 The Mass Evacuation from Dunkirk| publisher=Alan L.Putland| format=PDF| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> when [[Dunkirk evacuation|Operation Dynamo]] began, although an exception being [[HMS Wolsey|HMS ''Wolsey'']], a destroyer which was to act as a radio link ship.\n\n''Mona's Isle'' departed Dover at [[24-hour clock|21:00hrs]] on 27 May 1940.<ref name=\"dynamo\"/> The journey across the [[Strait of Dover|Channel]] during the hours of darkness was uneventful, and she arrived at Dunkirk at approximately [[24-hour clock|midnight.]] Once secured at the [[Wharf|quayside]], ''Mona's Isle'' embarked 1,420 troops<ref name=\"dynamo\"/> and she left at first light the next morning.\n\n[[File:Dunkirk Evacuation shipping routes.png|thumb|Map of the three evacuation routes]]Three routes were allocated to the evacuating vessels.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/operation_dynamo.html| title=Operation Dynamo, the evacuation from Dunkirk, 27 May-4 June 1940| author=Rickard, J| date=16 February 2008| publisher=Military History Encyclopedia on the Web| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> The shortest was '''Route Z''', a distance of 39 [[nautical miles]], which, after leaving Dunkirk followed the [[English Channel|French coast]] as far as No.6 Buoy, then turning [[Bearing (navigation)|Nor'west]] on a direct line to [[Dover]]. The longest of the three was '''Route Y''', a distance of 87 [[nautical miles]] that followed the French coast as far as Bray-Dunes then turned [[Bearing (navigation)|Nor'east]] until reaching the Kwinte Buoy.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IK8yWtpUyY0C&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=Kwinte+Buoy&source=bl&ots=rm5sPreVV9&sig=ZV-lj5Lt7ZmxN-_Uv-e1fKcIpJ4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qvt4UbSjJcXQOdusgbgP&sqi=2&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Kwinte%20Buoy&f=false| title=Dunkirk 1940: Operation Dynamo| author=Doug Dildy| author2=Howard Gerrard| publisher=Osprey Publishing| location=Oxford| year=2010| isbn=9781846034572| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> From there, after proceeding initially to the [[Bearing (navigation)|Nor'west]], ships then sailed in an westerly direction as far as the [[Goodwin Sands|North Goodwin Lightship]], then headed due south round the [[Goodwin Sands]] to Dover. The third, and although the safest from the German shore batteries, was through a heavily mined portion of the [[English Channel]]. This was '''Route X''', a distance of 55 nautical miles, and ships headed due north out of Dunkirk, through the Ruytingen Pass<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UqEOScq-AjUC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=Ruytingen+Pass&source=bl&ots=oCbRTLPOVS&sig=5hXX8eyaoX0F0j_mlBqMdGi50nA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EPV3Ud6zGYHkOrWggYgG&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Ruytingen%20Pass&f=false| title=The Evacuation from Dunkirk| author=W. J. R. Gardner| publisher=Frank Cass Publishers| year=2000| isbn=9780714651200| accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> and onto the North Goodwin Lightship before heading due south round the Goodwin Sands to Dover. The combination of the minefields and sandbanks meant passage via Route X was confined to daylight hours only.\n\nReturning by Route Z, the ''Mona's Isle'' came under fire from German shore batteries from the French coast. Many shells exploded close to the ship sending plumes of white water into the air and with water spraying over the decks. A number of shells failed to explode as they hit the ship, but one fell aft and smashed the rudder. The ''Mona's Isle'' was a triple screw vessel, so by careful use of port and starboard engines, the ship was able to reach the safety of Dover, but not before a [[Messerschmitt Bf 109|Bf 109]] had strafed the ship a couple of times killing 23 and wounding 60 others. Using the same route, two coasters, the ''Sequacity'' and the ''Yewdale'' headed for Dunkirk, and along the French coast they both came in for the same treatment. ''Sequacity'' suffered two direct hits, one into her starboard side, the other into the engine room and she started to sink, the crew being rescued by the ''Yewdale'', which aborted the mission and returned to [[Dover]].\n\nHowever ''Mona's Isle'' reached Dover safely, escorted by the [[Destroyer escort|destroyer]] [[HMS Windsor (D42)|HMS ''Windsor'']].\nThe mission had taken nearly 15 hours and she was recorded as the first ship to complete a round trip during the evacuation.<ref name=\"dynamo\"/>\n\nTwo awards were later made to members of the [[ship's company]] or their part in the action. The Commanding Officer, [[Commander|Cdr]] [[John Dowding (naval officer)|J.C.K. Dowding]] [[Royal Naval Reserve|RNR]], received the [[Distinguished Service Order]]. [[Petty Officer]] L.B. Kearley-Pope, [[Royal Naval Reserve|RNR]], was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Medal (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Medal]]. He had remained at a 12-pounder gun despite multiple wounds and he took a great risk in coming out of cover to close the [[cordite]] boxes. There were casualties among the gun's crew, but the PO continued to carry out his duties until the ship berthed six hours later. Cdr Dowding was later promoted to [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Captain]]. He was [[Commodore (rank)|Commodore]] of the ill-fated [[Convoy PQ 17]] to Russia, which was forced to scatter and suffered heavy losses in July 1942.\n\n''Mona's Isle'' made a second round trip to Dunkirk, bringing out a further 1,200 troops, and bringing her total to 2,634. The rest of her war service was spent either as an [[Ocean boarding vessel|Armoured Boarding Vessel]] or an accommodation ship. She was transferred to the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] in 1941, where she was three times involved in collisions, one of which did extensive damage and sent her to [[Drydock|dock]] for three months.\n\nOnce on the Tyne, where she lent support to the [[Anti-aircraft warfare|AA]] defences of coastal convoys, ''Mona's Isle'' gave valuable assistance on two occasions to [[Cargo ship|merchantmen]] that had been bombed, in one case rescuing 32 survivors. After [[D-Day]] she worked on cross-Channel transport duties until June 1945, when she was then chartered by the Ministry of War Transport before she was finally released from her war service in March 1946.\n\n===Post-war===\nAfter her war service, ''Mona's Isle'' returned to her duties within the Steam Packet fleet. She worked for a further two years, until with the introduction of the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company#The \"Six Sisters\"|\"Six Sisters\"]], she was withdrawn from service.\n\nAfter a thoroughly eventful life spanning 43 years, ''Mona's Isle'' was broken up at [[Milford Haven]] in 1948.\n\n==Gallery==\n\n{{gallery\n|title= RMS ''Mona's Isle''\n|width=250 | height=170 | lines=3\n|align=centre\n|image:Mona's Isle in the Mersey..JPG|''Mona's Isle'' in the [[River Mersey|Mersey]]\n|image:Mona's Isle enters Douglas Harbour..JPG|''Mona's Isle'' enters [[Douglas Harbour]]\n|image:Mona's Isle and Victoria.jpg|[[SS Victoria (1907)|''Victoria'']] (left) and ''Mona's Isle'' (right), during their winter lay-up at the Tongue, [[Douglas, Isle of Man]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* Chappell, Connery (1980). ''Island Lifeline'' T.Stephenson & Sons Ltd {{ISBN|0-901314-20-X}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Steam Packet Ships}}\n\n{{D